  "table-7.1": (
    caption: [Tissue concentrations of essential elements required by most plants, showing chemical symbols, concentrations in dry matter, and relative atomic abundances with respect to molybdenum. Elements are categorized into those obtained from water or carbon dioxide (hydrogen, carbon, oxygen) and those obtained from soil (macronutrients and micronutrients). This table provides a quantitative framework for understanding the nutritional requirements of plants and the vast differences in elemental needs ranging from hydrogen at 60 mg/g to molybdenum at 0.1 μg/g.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7.2": (
    caption: [Classification of plant mineral nutrients according to their biochemical functions. Nutrients are organized into four functional groups: Group 1 includes nutrients that are part of carbon compounds (nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus); Group 2 contains nutrients important for structural integrity (silicon, boron); Group 3 comprises nutrients that remain in ionic form (potassium, calcium, magnesium, chlorine, zinc, sodium); and Group 4 includes nutrients involved in redox reactions (iron, manganese, copper, nickel, molybdenum). This functional classification emphasizes the diverse physiological roles of mineral nutrients beyond simple macronutrient versus micronutrient distinctions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.1": (
    caption: [Solution culture systems for growing plants without soil. (A) Hydroponic culture system where plants are suspended over a nutrient solution tank with air pumped through a porous solid to generate oxygen-saturated bubbles. (B) Aeroponic growth system where a high-pressure pump sprays nutrient mist on roots enclosed in a chamber, with nutrient solution recovered and recycled. These systems enable precise control of nutrient availability for experimental studies and commercial crop production.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7.3": (
    caption: [Composition of a modified Hoagland nutrient solution for growing plants, showing compounds, molecular weights, stock solution concentrations, volumes needed, and final element concentrations. The formulation includes macronutrients (nitrogen, potassium, calcium, phosphorus, sulfur, magnesium) and micronutrients (chlorine, boron, manganese, zinc, copper, molybdenum, iron), with optional nickel and silicon. This solution represents a complete mineral nutrition medium that supports rapid plant growth under laboratory conditions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.2": (
    caption: [Examples of ferric iron-citrate complexes in solution and the effect of pH on their distribution. (A) Structure of HFe-citrate with zero charge. (B) Structure of Fe-citrate with 5- charge. (C) Graph showing the predominance of different ferric iron-citrate complex species as a function of pH from 2 to 8. At neutral pH, the Fe-citrate₂⁵⁻ species predominates. These complexes are crucial for maintaining iron solubility and availability in nutrient solutions and in plant tissues, as iron readily precipitates as hydroxides at alkaline pH.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7.4": (
    caption: [Mineral elements classified based on their mobility within plants and their tendency to retranslocate during deficiency conditions. Mobile elements include nitrogen, potassium, magnesium, sulfur, and phosphorus; elements with intermediate mobility include iron, zinc, copper, molybdenum, chlorine, and sodium; immobile elements include calcium and boron. This classification is critical for diagnosing nutrient deficiencies, as mobile nutrient deficiencies appear first in older leaves while immobile nutrient deficiencies manifest first in younger tissues.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-7.5": (
    caption: [Properties of different soil particle size classes showing particle diameter ranges, surface area per gram, and cation exchange capacity. Sand particles (0.05-2.0 mm) have low surface area (0.1 m²/g) and minimal cation exchange capacity. Silt particles (0.002-0.05 mm) have moderate properties. Clay particles (<0.002 mm) have very high surface area (10-1000 m²/g) and high cation exchange capacity. These physical properties determine soil water retention, nutrient availability, and overall fertility.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.3": (
    caption: [The effect of soil pH on the availability of plant nutrients. The diagram shows nutrient availability ranges from pH 4 to 10, with bar widths indicating relative availability. Most macronutrients (nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, sulfur, calcium, magnesium) are optimally available at pH 6.0-7.5. Micronutrients (iron, manganese, boron, copper, zinc) are generally more available under acidic conditions (pH 5.0-6.5), while molybdenum availability increases with pH. At extreme pH values, certain elements become either deficient or toxic, making pH management critical for plant nutrition.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.4": (
    caption: [Illustration of cation exchange capacity in soil showing the negative charges on clay particles and organic matter attracting and holding positively charged nutrient ions (cations) such as potassium, calcium, magnesium, and ammonium. These adsorbed cations are in equilibrium with ions in the soil solution and can be exchanged with other cations, including hydrogen ions. High cation exchange capacity soils can retain more nutrients and buffer against nutrient leaching, making them more fertile and productive for plant growth.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.5": (
    caption: [Fibrous root systems of wheat (a monocot) showing contrasting morphologies under different water conditions. (A) Root system of a mature 3-month-old wheat plant growing in dry soil shows limited branching and shallow penetration. (B) Root system of a mature wheat plant growing in irrigated soil displays extensive branching and deeper penetration. In mature fibrous root systems, primary root axes become indistinguishable. This demonstrates the remarkable plasticity of root architecture in response to environmental conditions, particularly water availability.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.6": (
    caption: [Harsh hakea (Hakea prostrata) produces cluster (proteoid) roots under phosphate deficiency conditions. (A) Comparison of harsh hakea plants grown with phosphate (left) showing normal root architecture versus without phosphate (right) showing cluster root formation. (B) Detailed view of a 7-day-old developing cluster root (right) and a mature cluster root (left). Cluster roots are dense aggregations of lateral roots that secrete large quantities of organic acids like citrate and malate, which lower soil pH and solubilize phosphate bound to calcium, aluminum, and iron, making it available for plant uptake.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.7": (
    caption: [Diagrammatic longitudinal section of the apical region of a root showing distinct zones of activity and tissue differentiation. The apex contains the quiescent center (region of slow cell divisions) covered by the root cap and mucigel sheath. The meristematic zone features rapid cell division. The elongation zone shows cells expanding primarily in the longitudinal direction. The maturation zone displays differentiated tissues including epidermis with root hairs, cortex, endodermis with Casparian strip, exodermis with Casparian strip, and the stele containing xylem and phloem. This organization is fundamental to understanding nutrient and water uptake along the root.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.8": (
    caption: [Three-dimensional plot showing root biomass as a function of extractable soil ammonium and nitrate concentrations. The surface plot displays root dry weight (μg/g soil) plotted against extractable soil ammonium and nitrate (μg nitrogen/g soil) for tomato plants growing in an irrigated field. Colors range from low biomass (purple) to high biomass (red). The data demonstrates that roots preferentially grow and proliferate in soil regions with higher nutrient availability, illustrating the principle of nutrient foraging and the heterogeneous distribution of roots in response to localized soil nutrient patches.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.9": (
    caption: [Topsoil foraging adaptations for phosphorus acquisition by phosphorus-efficient bean genotypes compared to non-adapted genotypes. Adapted genotypes display multiple modifications including more adventitious roots, shallower basal root angles, more dispersed lateral roots, longer and denser root hairs, smaller root diameter, formation of aerenchyma, increased root biomass in topsoil layers, enhanced secretion of exudates (organic acids, protons, phosphatases), and development of mycorrhizal associations. These architectural and biochemical changes concentrate root activity in surface soil horizons where phosphorus is most abundant, maximizing phosphorus uptake efficiency.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.10": (
    caption: [Root-to-shoot-to-root peptide signaling influences nitrate uptake in response to uneven nitrogen supply. (A) Split-root experiment with Arabidopsis showing one half of the root system on low nitrate (LN) and the other on high nitrate (HN), demonstrating preferential lateral root growth on the high-nitrate side after 5 days. (B) Model of C-terminally Encoded Peptide (CEP) signaling pathway: nitrogen starvation in roots induces CEP production, which travels via xylem to the shoot where it is perceived by CEP Receptors in the phloem. This triggers production of CEP Downstream (CEPD) proteins that travel back to roots via phloem to promote compensatory nitrogen uptake in high-nitrate regions. This exemplifies systemic nutrient demand signaling in plants.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.11": (
    caption: [Visualization of the intact extraradical mycelium of the arbuscular mycorrhizal fungus Glomus mosseae spreading from colonized roots of cherry plum (Prunus cerasifera). The advancing front of the extraradical mycelium (indicated by arrowheads) extends into the soil, while the plant root (indicated by arrow) serves as the colonization base. Note the striking differences in length and diameter between the thick plant roots and the fine fungal hyphae. The extensive hyphal network can explore soil volumes beyond the nutrient depletion zone and transport nutrients back to the host plant from distances up to 25 cm from the root surface.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.12": (
    caption: [Diagrammatic representation of the two major forms of arbuscular mycorrhizal colonization of the root cortex. (A) Arum-type colonization characterized by intercellular hyphae running between cortical cells and formation of intracellular highly branched arbuscules within individual cortical cells, along with vesicles for storage. (B) Paris-type colonization characterized by extensive intracellular hyphal coils within cortical cells, some forming arbusculate coils with small arbuscule-like branches. In both types, fungal structures remain confined to the cortex and do not penetrate the endodermis or stele. The arbuscules and coils are surrounded by plant membrane and serve as the interface for nutrient exchange between fungus and plant.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.13": (
    caption: [Diagrammatic longitudinal section of an ectomycorrhizal root showing the characteristic structural modifications. Fungal hyphae form a dense mantle layer completely covering the root surface. Hyphae penetrate between epidermal cells and sometimes between cortical cells to form the Hartig net, a network of intercellular hyphae that creates a large interface for nutrient exchange. The Hartig net does not penetrate individual cells. External hyphae extend extensively into the soil, forming mycelium and mycelial strands that explore soil organic matter and transport nutrients back to the root. The fungal mantle serves as an obligate pathway for all nutrients entering the root.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "figure-7.14": (
    caption: [Pine (Pinus) seedling showing ectomycorrhizal colonization in an observation chamber with forest soil. The image displays mycorrhizal rootlets (upper arrow) colonized by an ectomycorrhizal fungus, with a dense mycelial front of advancing hyphae growing into the soil (arrowheads), and aggregated mycelial strands (lower arrow) that provide long-distance nutrient transport. The extensive fungal mycelium often exceeds the root mass itself. Mycelial fans and strands are particularly effective at obtaining nutrients from soil organic matter, producing many of the mushrooms, puffballs, and truffles found in forests.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
